Now we will complete the proof for each of the four cases.

Case 1: `p = 0 ∧ q = 0 ∧ r = 0`. This is problematic as discussed. In Lean, this would be:
```tactics
· -- Case where all exponents are 0
  simp [dLpNorm_zero]
  all_goals try { tauto }
```
This case is actually false because `‖0‖_[0] = 1` and `‖0‖_[0] * ‖0‖_[0] = 1 * 1 = 1`, so `1 ≤ 1` is true. But if `f = 0` and `g ≠ 0`, then `‖0‖_[0] = 1`, `‖0‖_[0] = 1`, and `‖g‖_[0] = 0`, so `1 ≤ 1 * 0` is false. Similarly for `f ≠ 0` and `g = 0`. So this case is actually false.

Case 2: `p = 0 ∧ q ≠ 0 ∧ r = 1 / q`. This is also problematic. In Lean, this would be:
```tactics
· -- Case where p = 0, q ≠ 0, r = 1 / q
  simp [dLpNorm_zero]
  all_goals try { tauto }
```
This case is false because if `f = 0` and `g ≠ 0`, then `‖0‖_[1/q] = 1` (by `dLpNorm_zero`), `‖0‖_[0] = 1`, and `‖g‖_[q] = 0` (by `dLpNorm_zero` since `g ≠ 0`), so `1 ≤ 1 * 0` is false.

Case 3: `p ≠ 0 ∧ q = 0 ∧ r = 1 / p`. By symmetry, this is also false. In Lean, this would be:
```tactics
· -- Case where p ≠ 0, q = 0, r = 1 / p
  simp [dLpNorm_zero]
  all_goals try { tauto }
```
This case is false because if `g = 0` and `f ≠ 0`, then `‖0‖_[1/p] = 1`, `‖f‖_[p] = 0`, and `‖0‖_[0] = 1`, so `1 ≤ 0 * 1` is false.

Case 4: `p ≠ 0 ∧ q ≠ 0 ∧ r = (p * q) / (p + q)`. This is the standard case. In Lean, this would be:
```tactics
· -- Case where p ≠ 0, q ≠ 0, r = (p * q) / (p + q)
  have h1 : p ≠ 0 := by simpa using hp
  have h2 : q ≠ 0 := by simpa using hq
  have h3 : r = (p * q) / (p + q) := by simpa using hr
```
Now we can apply the standard Hölder inequality from `Mathlib`. The statement `‖f * g‖_[r] ≤ ‖f‖_[p] * ‖g‖_[q]` is precisely the Hölder inequality for the exponents `p, q, r` when `p, q > 0`. In Lean, this is likely to be available as a lemma.

```tactics
